text: The Ten Thousand Rooms project (https://t.co/NjwheqUHTX) is another annotation-focused project (run by my PhD advisor and another colleague at Yale). It is designed to allow collaborative analysis of high quality images of premodern Chinese imprints/manuscripts #dayofdh2020

text: Over the years libraries, universities, and others have put Chinese texts and historical data online (the Shanghai libray, for example,  hosts an open data portal, https://t.co/EY1iGCokPx, which provides access to genealogies and other linked data materials) #dayofdh2020

text: The Chinese Deathscape (https://t.co/BXxMszWbDW) is a digital monograph edited by @tsmullaney that examines the movement of graves in China. It encapsulates a lot of what makes public-facing humanities projects wonderful #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: A lot of folks are also out there building tools that make DH work in Chinese studies much easier: @hild_de's MARKUS project needs no introduction (and check out her #dayofdh2020 thread) and provides users with a platform for marking up Chinese (and Korean!) texts.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler

text: The Ming-Qing Women's Writings project (https://t.co/XNdkmSpYQv, led by Grace Fong at McGill) is another critical resource aimed at highlighting an understudied aspect of Chinese imperial literature. #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: We have an embarrassment of riches in online texts: CText (https://t.co/Ige7Eg3JJJ), the Kanseki Repository (https://t.co/p61f5HSH35), Open Literature (https://t.co/XdgAVxoxzk), Wikisource (https://t.co/vm11vx5kIf), and Daizhe Ge (https://t.co/sXc6f6kClx)... #dayofdh2020

name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: I could spend hundreds of tweets talking about wonderful Chinese DH research, but as I think about it, I fear I'll accidentally neglect to mention many of the incredible projects by scholars all over the world #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: So I'll just quickly mention three things: be sure to check out the November 2018 issue of the Journal of Chinese Literature and Culture, edited by @tommazanec, @thars3n, and Jing Chen. 8 spot-on articles covering a wide range of topics #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: This just represents a few of things I'm thinking about this morning, so I will miss a lot. I am an imperial lit scholar, so I have many blind spots. I love to hear about new things, so please jump in and highlight your favorite projects! #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: There are also MANY research databases out there, so I won't delve into them too much, but I would be remiss to neglect to mention the China Biographical Database (https://t.co/EgmQU7QM1l) #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: But beyond these infrastructural projects, one of the most exciting things about being involved in Chinese DH is the flowering of digital research! It is still a small field, but it is orders of magnitude larger than when I jumped in nearly 10 years ago. #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: I'll close this by saying that I have been privileged to watch Chinese Studies DH develop, and I am excited to see where this heads. Digital methods are beginning to organically merge with the larger Chinese research ecosystem and exciting things are coming #dayofdh2020!
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: On this #dayofdh2020 I'd like to take a few moments to highlight a few resources and projects in (and about) the Sinosphere, as this is still a somewhat hidden corner of the DH world.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler
description: Asst Prof @williamandmary Imperial Chinese Lit/Print History. Cultural analytics/ML. Kansan formerly at @LeidenDH. Views my own

text: As with digital humanities in other parts of the world, the earliest Chinese "DH" projects centered on creating text collections. The Chinese Buddhist Electronic Tripitaka Collection (https://t.co/fJAD7QjQiJ) dates from 1984! #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Paul Vierthaler

text: For #dayofdh2020 I'm making dinosaur lego with child1, and lulling child2 to sleep with Led Zep. In spare moments, I'm annotating place / object info in Pausanias using @PelagiosNetwork's https://t.co/BS24NYiPR4 incl alignment with @BradyKiesling's ToposText to create linked data
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Elton Barker
description: Working class classicist | Mapping texts explorer | Developing digital tools for humanists | Pelagios Community Director | Homer agonist | Ginger (formerly)

text: To link between texts and objects, we need (at least) two things: 1. gazetteers for urban spaces like Athens; 2. a way of "linking up" Pelagios's method of semantic annotation for documents and Getty's Linked Art vocabulary for describing cultural heritage objects #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Elton Barker
description: Working class classicist | Mapping texts explorer | Developing digital tools for humanists | Pelagios Community Director | Homer agonist | Ginger (formerly)

text: So far we're linking Pausanias's text to @BradyKiesling's https://t.co/SJZ2b3HP9P, Judith Binder's art historical database, and @dai_weltweit's object database https://t.co/LF1sKLfux9 But there's a lot more we could do: e.g. @ASCSAthens #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Elton Barker
description: Working class classicist | Mapping texts explorer | Developing digital tools for humanists | Pelagios Community Director | Homer agonist | Ginger (formerly)

text: One aspect of this annotation practice is to compare Pausanias's description to the situation on the ground as described by archaeology ‚Äî not to prove the author right or wrong, but to get a better sense of his *representation*, both its forms and ideologies #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Elton Barker
description: Working class classicist | Mapping texts explorer | Developing digital tools for humanists | Pelagios Community Director | Homer agonist | Ginger (formerly)

text: To do that, we also need to link from our annotations to other resources: e.g. the sites through which he moves, the objects he describes, not only to compare his descriptions, but also to identify the gaps in his account. What does Pausanias leave out, when, why? #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Elton Barker
description: Working class classicist | Mapping texts explorer | Developing digital tools for humanists | Pelagios Community Director | Homer agonist | Ginger (formerly)

text: Now I'm going back to Recogito which, in addition to enabling DIY semantic annotation (and linked data), collaborative analysis, and the mapping of narratives, gets me closer to the text. Slow reading for #dayofdh2020
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Elton Barker
description: Working class classicist | Mapping texts explorer | Developing digital tools for humanists | Pelagios Community Director | Homer agonist | Ginger (formerly)

text: What is annotation precisely? The practice goes back (at least) to the marginalia of manuscripts. What #Recogito enables is *semantic annotation* - attaching additional meaning to a concept: aligning a place reference in a document to a global authority / gazetteer #dayofdh2020
